[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] From a more abstract perspective, workflow may be considered a view or representation of real work.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The flow being described may refer to a document, service, or product that is being transferred from one step to another.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Workflows may be viewed as fundamental building blocks to be combined with other parts of an organization's structure, such as information technology, teams, projects, and hierarchies.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The development of the workflow concept occurred across several loosely defined, overlapping eras.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The modern history of workflows can be traced to Frederick Taylor and Henry Gantt, although the term "workflow" was not used in this context during their lifetimes.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] One of the earliest instances of the term "work flow" was in a railway engineering journal from 1921.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Taylor and Gantt launched the study of the deliberate, rational organization of work, primarily in the context of manufacturing.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] This gave rise to time and motion studies.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Related concepts include job shops and queuing systems (Markov chains).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The 1948 book *Cheaper by the Dozen* introduced the emerging workflow concept to the context of family life.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The invention of the typewriter and the copier helped spread the study of the rational organization of labor from the manufacturing shop floor to the office.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Filing and other sophisticated systems for managing physical information flows evolved.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Several events likely contributed to the development of formalized information workflows.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] First, the field of optimization theory matured and developed mathematical optimization techniques.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] For example, Soviet mathematician and economist Leonid Kantorovich developed the seeds of linear programming in 1939 through efforts to solve a plywood manufacturer's production optimization issues.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Second, World War II and the Apollo program drove process improvement forward with their demands for the rational organization of work.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Juran led to a focus on quality, first in Japanese companies, and more globally from the 1980s.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] There were various movements ranging from total quality management to Six Sigma, and then more qualitative notions of business process re-engineering.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] This led to more efforts to improve workflows in both knowledge economy sectors and manufacturing.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Thought leaders recognized variable demands on workflows when they considered the theory of critical paths and moving bottlenecks.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Basu and Kumar noted that the term "workflow management" referred to tasks associated with the flow of information through the value chain rather than the flow of material goods: they characterise the definition, analysis and management of information as "workflow management".
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The transmission of information from one organization to another is a critical issue in this inter-organizational context and raises the importance of tasks they describe as "validation", "verification" and "data usage analysis".
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A workflow management system (WfMS) is a software system for creating, executing, and monitoring a defined sequence of processes and tasks, with the broad goals of increasing productivity, reducing costs, becoming more agile, and improving information exchange within an organization.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] These systems may be process-centric or data-centric, and they may also represent the workflow as graphical maps.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A workflow management system may also include an extensible interface so that external software applications can be integrated, providing support for wide area workflows that provide both faster response times and improved productivity.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The workflow concept is closely related to several fields in operations research and other areas that study the nature of work either quantitatively or qualitatively, such as artificial intelligence (in particular, the sub-discipline of AI planning) and ethnography.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The term "workflow" is more commonly used in particular industries like printing, as well as professional domains such as clinical laboratories.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] It may have particular specialized meanings in these areas.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] **Planning and scheduling**: A plan is a description of the logically necessary, partially ordered set of activities required to accomplish a specific goal given certain starting conditions.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A plan, when augmented with a schedule and resource allocation calculations, completely defines a particular *instance* of systematic processing in pursuit of a goal.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A workflow may be viewed as an often optimal or near-optimal realization of the mechanisms required to execute the same plan repeatedly.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] **Flow control**: This is a control concept applied to workflows, to distinguish from static control of buffers of material or orders, to mean a more dynamic control of flow speed and flow volumes in motion and in process.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Such orientation to dynamic aspects is the basic foundation to prepare for more advanced job shop controls, such as just-in-time or just-in-sequence.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] **In-transit visibility**: This monitoring concept applies to transported material as well as to work in process or work in progress, i.e., workflows.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Insurance claims processing is an example of an information-intensive, document-driven workflow.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Wikipedia editing can be modeled as a stochastic workflow.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The Getting Things Done system is a model of personal workflow management for information workers.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] In software development, support and other industries, the concept of *follow-the-sun* describes a process of passing unfinished work across time zones.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] In scientific experiments, the overall process (tasks and data flow) can be described as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] This DAG is referred to as a workflow, e.g., Brain Imaging workflows.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] In healthcare data analysis, a workflow can be identified or used to represent a sequence of steps that comprise a complex data analysis.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] In service-oriented architectures, an application can be represented through an executable workflow, where different, possibly geographically distributed, service components interact to provide the corresponding functionality under the control of a workflow management system.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] In shared services, an application can be in the practice of developing robotic process automation (called RPA or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0 based on artificial intelligence) which results in the deployment of attended or unattended software agents to an organization's environment.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] These software agents, or robots, are deployed to perform pre-defined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Artificial intelligence software robots are deployed to handle unstructured data sets and are deployed after performing and deploying robotic process automation.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Measurement: Many of the concepts used to measure scheduling systems in operations research are useful for measuring general workflows.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] These include throughput, processing time, and other regular metrics.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Specialized connotations: The term "workflow" has specialized connotations in information technology, document management, and imaging.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Since 1993, one trade consortium specifically focused on workflow management and the interoperability of workflow management systems, the Workflow Management Coalition.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Scientific workflow systems: These found wide acceptance in the fields of bioinformatics and cheminformatics in the early 2000s, when they met the need for multiple interconnected tools that handle multiple data formats and large data quantities.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Also, the paradigm of scientific workflows resembles the well-established practice of Perl programming in life science research organizations, making this adoption a natural step towards more structured infrastructure setup.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Human-machine interaction: Several conceptualizations of mixed-initiative workflows have been studied, particularly in the military, where automated agents play roles just as humans do.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] For innovative, adaptive, and collaborative human work, the techniques of human interaction management are required.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Workflow analysis: Workflow systems allow users to develop executable processes with no familiarity with formal programming concepts.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Automated workflow analysis techniques can help users analyze the properties of user workflows to conduct verification of certain properties before executing them, e.g., analyzing flow control or data flow.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Examples of tools based on formal analysis frameworks have been developed and used for the analysis of scientific workflows and can be extended to the analysis of other types of workflows.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Several workflow improvement theories have been proposed and implemented in the modern workplace.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Resource evaluation (both physical and human) is essential to evaluating hand-off points and creating smoother transitions between tasks.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A workflow can usually be described using formal or informal flow diagramming techniques and displays directed flows between processing steps.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Components can only be plugged together if the output of one previous (set of) component(s) is equal to the mandatory input requirements of the following component(s).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Thus, the essential description of a component actually comprises only input and output that are described fully in terms of data types and their meaning (semantics).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] The algorithms' or rules' descriptions need only be included when there are several alternative ways to transform one type of input into one type of output – possibly with different accuracy, speed, etc.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] When the components are non-local services that are invoked remotely via a computer network, such as Web services, developers must consider additional descriptors (such as QoS and availability).
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] A workflow application is a software application that automates a process or processes to some degree.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] These processes are usually business-related but can be any process that requires a series of steps to be automated via software.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Some process steps may require human intervention, such as development and approval of custom text, but functions that can be automated should be handled by the application.
[src:aws-sfn-workflows/workflow] Advanced applications allow users to introduce new components into the operation.
